rations of how we imagine people wrote in bygone eras. Though Close Reading with Computers focuses on but one novel, it has a crucial exemplary function: author Martin Paul Eve demonstrates a set of methods and provides open-source software tools that others can use in their own literary-critical practices. In this way, the project serves as a bridge between users of digital methods and those engaged in more traditional literary-critical endeavors.  afunded by The Philip Leverhulme Prize  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aComputational linguisticsxMethodology. 0aCriticism, TextualxMethodologyxComputer programs. 0aDigital humanitiesxResearchxMethodology. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aClose reading.  aCloud Atlas.  aDavid Mitchell.  acritique.  adigital humanities.  adistant reading.  ahistorical fiction.  apublishing.  atextual scholarship.2 aThe Philip Leverhulme Prizeefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z97831106922800 cprintz978150360699940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503609372423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503609372/original  a978-3-11-069228-0  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-070471-6  